From the system of equations we derived:
\begin{align*}
5t + 15s &= 4 \\
2t + 6s &= k - 1
\end{align*}

We can simplify this system by dividing the first equation by 5:
\begin{align*}
t + 3s &= \frac{4}{5} \\
2t + 6s &= k - 1
\end{align*}

Next, we can express the second equation in terms of $t$ and substitute the value of $t$ from the first equation:
\begin{align*}
2(t + 3s) &= k - 1 \\
2\left(\frac{4}{5}\right) &= k - 1 \\
\frac{8}{5} &= k - 1 \\
k &= \frac{13}{5}
\end{align*}

Hence, the value of $k$ such that the equation has infinitely many solutions in $t$ and $s$ is $\boxed{\frac{13}{5}}$.
